Set Up

Start by loading packages and data:

library(tidyverse)
voters_sos <- 
  read_csv("data/registered voters/voters_SOS/voters_SOS.csv")

I donât love the way the Secretary of State classifies party affiliation. So I will be making two graphs for each type of graph: one with the SoS party affiliations and one with my own definitions.

My definition: To be affiliated with a political party, you must have voted in that partyâs primary in the past three elections and not in any other partyâs primary within that time period.

Is it perfect? No.

Thatâs why I will be making every graph with the SoS definition too. This will provide a sense of standardization.

voters_sos <- voters_sos %>%
  mutate(party = NA) %>% 
  mutate(
    party = ifelse(!is.na(PARTY_AFFILIATION), 
                   PARTY_AFFILIATION,
                   case_when(
                     (`PRIMARY.03/19/2024` == "R") |
                       (`PRIMARY.03/19/2024` == "o" & `PRIMARY.03/17/2020` == "R") |
                       (`PRIMARY.03/19/2024` == "o" & `PRIMARY.03/17/2020` == "o" &
                          `PRIMARY.03/15/2016` == "R") ~ "R",
                     
                     (`PRIMARY.03/19/2024` == "D") |
                       (`PRIMARY.03/19/2024` == "o" & `PRIMARY.03/17/2020` == "D") |
                       (`PRIMARY.03/19/2024` == "o" & `PRIMARY.03/17/2020` == "o" &
                          `PRIMARY.03/15/2016` == "D") ~ "D",
                     
                     TRUE ~ party  # Retain existing value if no condition is met
                   )
    )
  ) %>% 
  mutate(party = ifelse(is.na(party),
                        "U",
                        party))
voters_sos <- voters_sos %>% 
  mutate(PARTY_AFFILIATION = ifelse(is.na(PARTY_AFFILIATION),
                        "U",
                        PARTY_AFFILIATION))

A little bit of comparison between my definition and the SoS definition:

table(voters_sos$party)

     D      R      U 
128447 124725 350877 
table(voters_sos$PARTY_AFFILIATION)

     D      R      U 
 58840  71856 473353

Graphs with SoS Definition

Letâs prepare the data to examine the ages of voters for each political party.

ages_summary <- voters_sos %>%
  filter(AGE < 111) %>% 
  group_by(AGE, PARTY_AFFILIATION) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  ungroup()

Now letâs look at the age distribution for all registered voters by political party.

ages_summary %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = AGE, y = count, color = PARTY_AFFILIATION)) +
  geom_line() +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("D" = "blue", "R" = "red", "U" = "green")) +
  labs(title = "Number of People by Age and Party",
       x = "Age (Years)",
       y = "Number of People",
       color = "Party Affiliation") +
  theme_minimal()

Now each one separate:

  ungroup()
